{"name":"safe-http-close","version":"1.0.1","description":"Close an http server even if it isn't running","main":"index.js","scripts":{"lint":"eslint --ignore-path .gitignore .","test":"npm run lint && node test.js"},"repository":"https://github.com/lanetix/node-safe-http-close","keywords":["http","close","safe"],"license":"MIT","homepage":"https://github.com/lanetix/node-safe-http-close#readme","devDependencies":{"eslint":"^0.21.0","eslint-plugin-nodeca":"^1.0.3","noop2":"^1.0.1","tape":"^4.0.0"},"dependencies":{"curry":"^1.2.0"},"gitHead":"d4d737489b6ac66a562aaa0ea12c8349fd3d1b3d","versions":[{"number":"1.0.0","date":"2015-05-12T14:06:03.582Z"},{"number":"1.0.1","date":"2015-05-12T14:09:11.919Z"}],"readme":"safe-http-close\n====================\n`httpServer.close` will (throw in node < 0.12) callback with an error if the\nserver is still running. This is not what you want if you're just cleaning up\nconnections as part of your server's shutdown procedure. This libary provides\na function for you to safely close your server\n\nInstallation\n------------\n\n```bash\nnpm install safe-http-close\n```\n\nUsage\n-----\n\nInstead of calling `httpServer.close`, do\n\n```javascript\nvar safeClose = require('safe-http-close');\n\nsafeClose(server, function (err) {\n  if (!err) { console.log('closed'); }\n});\n```\n","created":"2015-05-12T14:06:03.582Z","modified":"2017-05-23T20:40:12.387Z","lastPublisher":{"name":"lanetix","email":"systems@lanetix.com"},"owners":[{"email":"lxpartnerdevelopment@lanetix.com","name":"lxpartnerdev"},{"email":"lougenia.bailey@gmail.com","name":"lougenia"},{"email":"sara.j.martinez@gmail.com","name":"smartinez"},{"email":"mbcrute@gmail.com","name":"mbcrute"},{"email":"apeherder@gmail.com","name":"apechimp"},{"email":"dlw405@gmail.com","name":"wiedld"},{"email":"ruthlesshelp@gmail.com","name":"ruthlesshelp"},{"email":"karenwsit@gmail.com","name":"karenwsit"},{"email":"bryan.murphy@lanetix.com","name":"bryan.murphy"},{"email":"jcready@gmail.com","n